description.text: I liked ssd's thumb crank, but it was rough around the edges (literally and figuratively) and just didn't feel quite right. My finger kept slipping off of it when it turned, and I realized that it needed a narrower shaft to allow the finger to get some purchase, and I wanted to figure out how to make those sweet curved contours with rounded edges in OpenSCAD (hint: lots of toriods). This is the result. It works extremely well and feels disconcertingly good turning around the finger. Best of all, it's made in OpenSCAD, and is fully parametric.

The hole should be about .5mm smaller than the rod (the STL is sized for the makerbot M8 Z-rods), and should screw on tightly, self-threading as it goes. Like ssd's crank, it should be tight enough to not need a set screw, but if you've got screwy tolerances on your printer that make it too loose, you can always change the bore variable in the scad file.

title: Symmetric-hinge Polygon Elements
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: Polyhedron components with symmetric(unsigned) hinges. Also, now with octagon. The previous kit http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4934 had larger facets and signed snaps, and assembly was a puzzle. This script resolves these problems by using only one symmetric hinge. I adapted a concept from http://www.thingiverse.com/twotimes to design these hinges. These parts are snap and dimensionally compatible with other things tagged "Elements". They are also useful starting blanks for building up more Element-compatible things. If you noticed that this is a duplicate of the "circular elements" thing, you're right. I posted renderings separately for those who don't want to invoke OpenSCAD scripts.

For trippy patterns to get started, visit
http://www.geometrycode.com/sg/archimedeans.shtml. Print using a heated build plate. The pieces have extra plastic to pin down the hinges: remove this with a razor knife. This will also rounds out the bottom of the hinge providing the full range of motion. Since these snaps are unsigned, simply lay out your polyhedron design as if building out of folded paper. Keep either the top or bottom side of the printed piece oriented consistently so the snaps will line up properly. http://www.thingiverse.com/Renosis built an epic polyhedron with the old kit. Hopefully this set will be easier to work with, but I haven't tested the triangles yet. I'm eager to see how larger forms look. update : These hold together too well. Some of the snaps were damaged when I took apart the dodecahedron I'd made. This can easily be fixed by reducing the number of clips from 6 to 4. If you examine the script, there is a clear example of how to do this down toward the bottom where the triangular piece is defined. Let me know if you want me to render these and post them, or any other design modifications you might want. note on hinge clearance : The hinges can sometimes be a little tight. Make sure the first layer isn't pressed too far into the build platform. A compressed first layer will propagate up and make part of the hinge wider, decreasing the clearance. These parts are designed to fit tightly and may require pliers to assemble. If all else fails, removing some of the pins on the hinges can make assembly easier.

The Constellation: In 1954, Hoover introduced the Model 82 Constellation. It was a radically new design in cylinder and tank cleaners. Designed by Henry Dreyfuss, it represented America's obsession with the space race. Its spherical shaped mimicked developing space technology. Its most memorable attribute was the ability to "walk on air", which eliminated the need for casters, wheels or runners. The cleaner was made mobile by using its exhaust air, which caused the cleaner to lift from the floor and float behind the user (starting with the Model 84). This was an engineering marvel in and of itself. The Constellation cleaner remained extremely popular in its close to 25-year run, with minor design modifications. The machine was discontinued in the mid-1970s with the introduction of the Hoover Celebrity. The machine was so fondly remembered that it was reintroduced and sold from 2006 to 2009.

3D Design Services by MakerBot created the Hand Mixer to showcase some of the intricate possibilities that 3D printing can bring to the industrial design, prototyping, and product design processes.   
Our designers expertly crafted it to gracefully enclose mechanical components, simulate color breakups/over-molding, and reliably print on a MakerBot Replicator 3D Printer while featuring realistic replications of the machine’s components — including the control dial, worm gears, motor assembly (magnets, shaft, cooling fan), shell, mounting bosses, and screw bosses.  
All pieces print without support.

description.text: I made this to replace the handle and lever on my son's shark grabber toy (see photos) after the brittle plastic it came with shattered.

My only print of this thing, at 10mm tube diameter and allowing SketchUp to resize the model, resulted in not enough tolerance and a fused mechanism. Because I loath to waste a print; I cleaned the support material, removed the canopy, added a pin .... it works! Caveat, cleaning the support materials from this thing will probably not be easy at much smaller than 20mm tube diameter (with model resized).
  • Set tube diameter to be compatible with pillar of broken toy. Resize model as necessary.
  • Print with support materials.
  • Clean and with luck it moves.

description.text: A modification to accommodate the bearing from the original mod.  If you don't want to buy more bearings and you trust PLA to a smaller diameter bearing post, you are the target demo.

Despite being a chamfer, you get a ball (roofing?).  I cut this off and popped the bearing on and sealed the cover by briefly exposing the joint to a preheated nozzle.

This is a mount for a standard 40mm fan, designed specifically to fit the Hexagon Hotend. It fits the cooling fins very tightly, and directs the airflow from the fan across the them.   
With an all-metal hotend like the Hexagon, it is extremely important to have a fan to keep the cool side from becoming too warm and melting the filament too high up.   
This mount friction fits tight enough to the cooling fins that it will stay in place, but I highly recommend adding a zip-tie to make sure it stays in place.  
I have only used this mount on my Kossel Mini, but it should fit on any printer using the Hexagon Hotend. It is designed connect to the hotend without relying on other parts of the printer so that it is more universal.

title: GoPro3 mounts for ZMR250 + ANY Quadcopter + anti-vibration mount.

description.text:
I wanted to create a better way to fit my GoPro to the stock anti-vibration mounts on my ZMR250 mini quad. The stock GoPro frame and mount sits the camera too high and this causes the camera to wobble excessively. This design will allow easy fitment of the camera into the case and give the GoPro a very sturdy structure to film from. Print the two components and line up the holes on the bottom, then glue them together. Simple. I tried a few different designs to have them interlocking but I didn't want it to come apart in-flight. Also the camera is slightly off-center because of the camera's CofG, so the vibration mounts will work better since the camera and frame will be perfectly balanced between the four anti-vibration balls. I am in the process of printing the first prototype so it's not fully tested yet. Thanks to Marfusio for the Gopro Hero3 frame which I tweaked to suit my silver model. I added a few extra holes to reduce the weight and final print cost on 3dHubs.com other than that I basically removed the GoPro mounts at h bottom so the frame and camera has a lower center of gravity. Remix of: Marfusio's GoPro Hero3 mounting frame (Black Edition) http://www.thingiverse.com/Marfusio/about http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:76082 If you have any design suggestions or if you have any problems, let me know. So far this is the only design like this on the web so good luck and have fun. Enjoy. 20JAN15 - uploaded the .skp file so you can make changes as required for various models. Also, I decided to attach the two pieces together with strong double sided tape so I can do some testing, so far the case fits perfectly and initial testing has returned some pretty good footage. It is very easy to use and looks great. Let me know how you go.
28FEB15 - I am excited to upload an updated base to incorporate a 10degree tilt for the GoPro frame to capture footage during high speed flight. I am yet to test this version out on a printer and it was a quick build so if you have any feedback - let me know. Otherwise enjoy the modified base. Thanks guys for the feedback so far and if you have any requests or good ideas pass them my way and I will do my best. Enjoy. I think I fixed the problem with the STL file not being solid enough plus rounded the edges of the rectangle at the front for some extra strength and a cleaner print. If you have any problems let me know.
28May15 - A friend asked me to make a GoPro mount to fit his quadcopter, this is what I came up with. Its bit of a variation on my original print. I think I prints out much better that the first one and I will upload the modified files when I get a chance.
30May15 - I have uploaded some new models! My revised design from the original version, larger holes to minimize weight but also to improve the print quality. The new anti-vibration mount has some elevated portions to help hold in cable ties in place. I found this made the camera more secure and reduced camera movement during heavy maneuvering. I have also added the basic GoPro Case I modified make the basic quadcopter mount. You can use this model and customize it for what ever you need. The photos I have used are just basic renders using free software though the sketchup download section but I find they do a good job, maybe better than my iPhone photos turn out anyway.
1Jun15 - CaseV1.3 uploaded which makes the frame about 1mm wider in portions so it prints better. There has been a few prints failed with and without supports printed so this should fix that.

Print two components using 3dhubs.com Line up holes on the bottom of both components Glue together (update: or use double sided tape if you are not sure) Insert Anti-vibration mounts on your ZMR250 Quadcopter Insert GoPro Hero3 Press Record and go flying. Give Rabbs355 some feedback so this can b made even better.

Inspired by the Hovership MHQ2, the MVQ (Mini V-Tail Quad) should make for an awesome 3D Printed FPV Racer with naturally increased yaw control beyond the torque-differential employed by typical x-frame quads. The MVQ is also an ideal test platform for advanced printing techniques for improving flight performance. This is only my second multirotor build and my first attempt at designing one: I'm still learning, testing and improving, so please bear with me. Check out the "instructions" for my setup and build thoughts. Features:
  • 250 Class Mini Quad Copter
  • 45° V-Angle
  • Ability to use MHQ2 Landing Gear and Arms
  • Provisions for Hovership Micro Power Distribution Board
  • <6oz Airframe Weight (ABS w/ Infill described)
  • 5 and 6 Inch props can be used without extended arms
    • Future Plans:
  • Camera Platforms (GoPro, Replay, etc...)
  • Forward Tilted Motors (Level Forward Flight)
  • Arms Designed for LED Mounting
  • Improvements From Testing!

Here's a quick run down of the MVQ specifics, I'll have proper instructions uploaded as time permits. Printing: My prototypes have been printed in ABS with the following parameters:
  • 200x200mm Print Bed Minimum
  • No additional support required (designed-in for trouble areas)
  • Landing Gear & Arms: 3 Perimeters, 75% Infill.
  • Base Plates: 3 Perimeters, 45% Infill.
  • Avionics Plates: 2 Perimeters, 35% Infill.
  • Battery Spacer: 2 Perimeters, Minimum Infill
    • Assembly:

  • Same hardware as MHQ2, with the addition of:
    +1X M3x20 Button Head Screw
    +1X M3 Lock Nut

  • Glue the battery spacers to the bottom of lower base with your choice of adhesive, locating pins make alignment simple.

  • Pins between upper and lower base parts should be a Gentle Press Fit, depending on your printer you may need to clean up the holes and/or pins.

  • V-motors are mounted down but props are oriented to lift up (Reference your Flight Controller documentation for rotation and mixing details).
    • My Setup:
  • ReadyToFlyQuads: Flip 2.5 Flight Controller
  • Bluetooth Adapter for PID Tuning
  • Hovership: Micro Power Dist. Board
  • Hovership: 12A ESC
  • Hovership: H2204X 2300KV Motors
  • 5x3 Props (HQ Prop)
  • Turnigy Nano-Tech 1500 mAh 3s 35C (9.5 minute flight time).

title: Spool Holder that clip in the spool with standard ball bearing

description.text:
I wanted a spool holder that clip on the spool and use as less space as possible because I will put my spools on a threaded rod over the printer in my rack-mount, so I can put 5 spools in one bar! Also this spool holder use a standard ball bearing, so it turn very smoothly. The STL file work with a standard skateboard ball bearing (22mm x 7mm), inside spool diameter of 56.5mm and tickness of 6mm. SCAD file is included so you can set your spool size, see instruction. UPDATED 2014-12-17:
With the suggestion of sgraber, I added 2 new variables to remove the locking ring and disable the hole to save PLA. Also now the hole to save PLA will work with smaller diameter of any size. UPDATED 2014-12-19:
Youtube video added: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p5wZdxiFyGA UPDATED 2014-12-20:
Updated SCAD script, I changed some variable name (bug from find & replace) and corrected a bug with the spool tickness. Also I added a new STL with different dimension, I use both of this configuration. UPDATED 2014-12-21:
New youTube video added with more spools
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lng9eZjR9RE&list=UUg0rSjryYrw6MFuhJREnz4w UPDATED 2015-01-03: Updated SCAD to support better bigger ball bearing size and bigger spool diameter

• Customize the openscad script for the desired spool dimension
    • The only thing you need to set is the spool_inside_diameter and spool_tickness so that your spool holder fit correctly on your spool. Once set, save and build the model, once build, export the STL file on your printer.

  • Print the spool holder without support material.

  • Install the skateboard ball bearing (22mmx7mm)
